{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d21dbe6c-2ea5-48a6-a69f-718d62e29de1","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to them:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |\n\nAlternatively, you can subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, etc. for a pattern closer to what you had before.\n\nFor **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks (e.g., Android `OnActivityResult`), use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7c238dee-f755-4c90-99a1-0dde064968f4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated()`\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped` event\n\n\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated` event\n\nThe `Application` class still exists in .NET MAUI but no longer exposes those lifecycle overrides. Instead, you work directly with the `Window` class and its lifecycle events like `Created`, `Resumed`, and `Stopped`, or you can hook into platform-specific lifecycle events through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`.\n\nThere's also a `Destroying` event for cleanup, and you can override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class to return a custom `Window` or subscribe to these events directly.","outputTokens":686,"requestId":"77CB:1E7A6A:8300DC6:912626F:69EABE91"},"id":"6e68948e-109a-4334-833d-2162f726f7ee","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:51:44.153Z","parentId":"33e236cc-3f4b-42ab-9223-b5b0f5b824e6"}
